# Service Layer Best Practices (meApp iOS)

## 1. Folder & File Organization
- Define all service interfaces (protocols) in `Domain/Services/`.
- Implement services in `Data/Services/`.
- Use clear, descriptive file and type names (e.g., `AccountService`, `IAccountService`).

## 2. Interface & Implementation
- Service interfaces must be pure Swift (no UIKit/SwiftUI dependencies).
- Use `async`/`await` for all asynchronous operations.
- Document all methods and protocols with SwiftDoc.
- Implementations must conform to the interface and be injected via DI.
- Use `@MainActor` only for UI-related services; otherwise, prefer actor isolation for shared mutable state.

## 3. Concurrency & Thread-Safety
- Prefer actor-isolated services for shared mutable state; use `nonisolated` functions only for read-only methods.
- Expose long-running operations as `AsyncStream` or `AsyncThrowingStream` so callers can observe progress or partial results.
- Always propagate cooperative cancellation (`Task.isCancelled`, `try Task.checkCancellation()`) and respect timeouts.

## 4. Error & Result Handling
- Model failures with domain-specific enum types conforming to `LocalizedError`.
- Avoid throwing raw `URLError`s or system errors from services.
- Provide retry/back-off helpers in the service layer so UI code stays declarative.
- Offer a non-throwing `Result<Value, DomainError>` overload for ergonomic call sites.

## 5. Dependency Injection
- All services must be injected via a DI container (e.g., `DependencyContainer`).
- Register services in a central registry (e.g., `ServiceRegistry`).
- Use singletons only when stateless or when state must be shared app-wide.

## 6. Documentation
- Every service interface and implementation must have clear SwiftDoc comments.
- Document the purpose, parameters, return values, and error cases for each method.
- For complex logic, add inline comments explaining the reasoning or algorithm.

## 7. Testing
- All business logic in services must be unit tested.
- Use mock or fake implementations for testing.
- Test error cases, cancellation, and retry logic.

## 8. General Best Practices
- Keep services focused and single-responsibility.
- Avoid business logic in UI or repository layers; keep it in services.
- Use value types for immutable data and reference types for shared mutable state.
- Prefer composition over inheritance.
- Ensure all public APIs are thread-safe.
- Avoid side effects in service initializers; use explicit methods for setup/teardown.

---

**Summary:**
- All business logic must be in services, with clear interfaces, DI, documentation, concurrency safety, robust error handling, and thorough testing.
